			<a href="http://wiep.net" rel="external nofollow" title="Wiep"><img alt='Wiep' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/3b77d32e346ce9d37a4106ad00931b83?s=50&amp;d=&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' /></a>
			<div class="comment-meta"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://wiep.net"><a href="http://wiep.net" title="Wiep" class="url" rel="external">Wiep</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Monday, November 10th, 2008, 9:31 pm">November 10, 2008</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Monday, November 10th, 2008, 9:31 pm">21:31</abbr></span>  &middot; </div>
			<div class="comment-content comment-text">
				
				
				<p>Great post, Tad.</p>
<p>Dofollow hunters suck and are pretty easy to spot. You&#8217;ll see a new visitor popping in via an online dofollow blog spam list of some sort, followed by a comment from someone named &#8216;Profesional SEO company&#8217; -which is a pretty weird name, even for a misspelling-, leaving a comment that barely says anything&#8230; Yuck!</p>
<p>It&#8217;s stupid not to mention your URL when you&#8217;re commenting on a blog while you&#8217;re building links, but it&#8217;s even more stupid to just drop your link <i>because</i> you&#8217;re building links&#8230;</p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content .comment-text -->

			
		</div><!-- .comment-wrap -->

		
	</li><!-- .comment -->
