			<a href="http://www.merlinsilk.com" rel="external nofollow" title="Merlin Silk"><img alt='Merlin Silk' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/8b50bc554fc3e2452472287b5af47fe4?s=50&amp;d=&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' /></a>
			<div class="comment-meta"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://www.merlinsilk.com"><a href="http://www.merlinsilk.com" title="Merlin Silk" class="url" rel="external">Merlin Silk</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Tuesday, November 11th, 2008, 8:05 am">November 11, 2008</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Tuesday, November 11th, 2008, 8:05 am">08:05</abbr></span>  &middot; </div>
			<div class="comment-content comment-text">
				
				
				<p>I compare this to an advise from an accountant-friend many years back in Germany: He told me not to buy any property just for tax reasons &#8211; even without the element of saving taxes it must still be a good investment. Applying this to blog commenting means that writing the comment should be a good investment (in your time) even if there was no google. That also means that it does not matter if the blog is follow or no-follow. If investing the time to write that comment is a good one, then do it. Even if at this time Google might not be able to see the semantics in the comment, at one point it will be able to, and then that link will become also relevant for link building.</p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content .comment-text -->

			
