	<li id="comment-68218" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 reader has-avatar">

		
		<div class="comment-wrap">

			
			<a href="http://www.webhostingsecretrevealed.com" rel="external nofollow" title="Jerry @ Web Hosting Secret Revealed"><img alt='Jerry @ Web Hosting Secret Revealed' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/2753ecf6d0a9257ec3ad1537e357abaa?s=50&amp;d=&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' /></a>
			<div class="comment-meta"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://www.webhostingsecretrevealed.com"><a href="http://www.webhostingsecretrevealed.com" title="Jerry @ Web Hosting Secret Revealed" class="url" rel="external nofollow">Jerry @ Web Hosting Secret Revealed</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Monday, November 17th, 2008, 7:47 am">November 17, 2008</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Monday, November 17th, 2008, 7:47 am">07:47</abbr></span>  &middot; </div>
			<div class="comment-content comment-text">
				
				
				<blockquote><p>So does commenting on dofollow-blogs make sense as a link building strategy? No, it doesn’t.</p></blockquote>
<p>No I disagree. You can say spam-commenting on dofollow blog is unethical but it does make perfect sense for SEO. </p>
<p>When you&#8217;re aiming on long tail, low-to-average competition SERP, blog commenting works (which explains why people are doing it) &#8211; it simply improve a site&#8217;s ranking. In fact the ranking can be lifted drastically if your comment slips into a related blog with high authority.</p>
<p>Proof? Check out the blog ranking mid (i wouldn&#8217;t name the site) on this SERP: <a href="http://www.google.com/search?q=review+lunarpages&#038;sourceid=navclient-ff&#038;ie=UTF-8&#038;rlz=1B3GGGL_enMY239MY242" rel="nofollow">http://www.google.com/search?q=review+lunarpages&#038;sourceid=navclient-ff&#038;ie=UTF-8&#038;rlz=1B3GGGL_enMY239MY242</a></p>
