	<li id="comment-69996" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 reader has-avatar">

		
		<div class="comment-wrap">

			
			<a href="http://optempo.com" rel="external nofollow" title="Frank Carr"><img alt='Frank Carr' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/55fd4fda0129242f31572e2e56d64e37?s=50&amp;d=&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' /></a>
			<div class="comment-meta"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://optempo.com"><a href="http://optempo.com" title="Frank Carr" class="url" rel="external nofollow">Frank Carr</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Thursday, November 27th, 2008, 5:41 am">November 27, 2008</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Thursday, November 27th, 2008, 5:41 am">05:41</abbr></span>  &middot; </div>
			<div class="comment-content comment-text">
				
				
				<p>I think that what comes into play here is that a lot of high PR dofollow blogs end up with a lot of &#8216;link juice dilution&#8217; on the high PR posts. If there were only 5-10 comments then a good amount of juice would be passed but when there are 50+ there is a lot of dilution of PR.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m rather confident that commenting on dofollow blogs works well when this dilution isn&#8217;t allowed by the blog owner performing vigilant moderation.</p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content .comment-text -->

			
