			<img alt='Steve' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/83707174f6514d1f4a86e04f1886e606?s=50&amp;d=&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />
			<div class="comment-meta"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn">Steve</cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Wednesday, December 31st, 2008, 11:57 am">December 31, 2008</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Wednesday, December 31st, 2008, 11:57 am">11:57</abbr></span>  &middot; </div>
			<div class="comment-content comment-text">
				
				
				<p>One common misconception is that if you go to a site with high PR, you have to have your link on the page that has the high PR, and if you go to a page with no PR, you don&#8217;t get credit for having the link on an authority site.</p>
<p>When asked about this, Matt Cutts basically said no comment.  IMO, his silence is deafening</p>
