			<div class="comment-meta"><span class="comment-author vcard"><cite class="fn" title="http://www.theravive.com"><a href="http://www.theravive.com" title="Arthur" class="url" rel="external nofollow">Arthur</a></cite></span><!-- .comment-author .vcard --> <span class="published"><abbr class="comment-date" title="Friday, January 2nd, 2009, 10:10 pm">January 2, 2009</abbr> at <abbr class="comment-time" title="Friday, January 2nd, 2009, 10:10 pm">22:10</abbr></span>  &middot; </div>
			<div class="comment-content comment-text">
				
				
				<p>I just learned about do-follow links and, in all honesty, I was wondering if attempting a campaign of blog-commenting would be a valid SEO approach to marketing.  Something in my gut says that it would be worthless and that Google could easily be smart enough to &#8220;notice&#8221; a site trying to spam blogs.  I think, in general, when it comes to SEO, if it starts looking unnatural, even if it feels unnatural, a smart SE like Google will pick up on it, and who knows, it could even hurt your PR in the end (yes remember how Google punished all those pay-per-post bloggers)?  So thank you for this article, I think I&#8217;ll listen to my instincts and rescind my plan for blog-spamming</p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content .comment-text -->

			
